-- Rebar Trades Near Lowest in Four Months on Inventory Concerns
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2013-04-24T02:47:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-24/rebar-trades-near-lowest-in-four-months-on-inventory-concerns.html
Steel reinforcement-bar futures in
 Shanghai  fell for a third day to the lowest in more than four
months as investors remained concerned about high inventories.  The contract for October delivery on the Shanghai Futures
Exchange declined as much as 0.5 percent to 3,581 yuan ($580) a
metric ton, the lowest level since Dec. 5, and was at 3,599 at
10:14 a.m. local time.  Rebar inventory  in  China  was at 9.85 million tons on April
19, up 82 percent since the end of last year, according to
Shanghai Steelhome Information. The government gave the go-ahead
to Shandong Steel Co.’s 8.5 million ton a year plant in Rizhao
on April 22.  “The oversupply situation remains unchanged,” Wang
Yongliang, an analyst at Beijing CIFCO Futures Co., said by
phone from Tianjin today.  Spot  iron ore  at Tianjin port fell 1.2 percent to $136.40 a
dry ton yesterday, the lowest since April 5, the Steel Index Ltd.
data show. Iron ore prices may average $125 a ton in the fourth
quarter, compared with a previous estimate of $130 in January,
Morgan Stanley said in a report yesterday.  The average  spot price  for rebar dropped 0.2 percent to
3,578  yuan  a ton yesterday, according to the Beijing Antaike
Information Development Co.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
